<TITLE> RAB 'crossfire' killed 373 during emergency: Sahara </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Mar 16 (bdnews24.com) - Some 373 criminals were killed in 'crossfire' involving the Rapid Action Battalion during two years of emergency rule, home minister advocate Sahara Khatun told parliament on Monday. In reply to a written question by Netrokona-5's Waresat Hossain Belal MP, the home minister said during the two years, one RAB member was killed and 175 were injured in raids and arms recovery drives. CCTV cameras to be set at 59 city points Answering a question from AKM Ramatullah MP, from Dhaka-10, Sahara Khatun said some 155 close-circuit TV cameras will be installed at 59 points in the capital under the project to modernise DMP control rooms. "Venues have already been decided and construction of infrastructure nearly completed," she informed parliament. "Some 14 CCTV cameras have been set up in five spots up to Feb 28." 334 Indians detained While replying to Rashed Khan Menon MP, of Dhaka-8, Sahara said some 334 Indian citizens were serving different jail terms in Bangladeshi prisons. "They are usually deported at the end of the sentence or detention periods." Tribal population is 15 lakh To a query from Naogaon-2's M Shahiduzzaman MP, planning minister AK Khandaker said the country's tribal population is 15.98 lakh, according to a March 2009 projection. bdnew
